ph_descripcion: Photo by @irina_sigl_photography | I photographed these beautiful beech trees in Jasmund National Park on the island of Rügen, part of a UNESCO World Heritage site. If you look at them from below, you can see that their tops never touch, as if they’ve agreed to keep a respectful distance from each other and still be close. This interesting phenomenon is called crown shyness. Nikon Z7, 14mm, f8, 1/1000s, ISO200. #YourShotPhotographer #Rügen

ph_descripcion: Photo by Doug Gimesy @doug_gimesy| A Rakali From Any Angle | Meet Hippo, a 10- to 14-day-old rakali (Hydromys chrysogaster) at Mount Gambier Wildlife Carer. Rakalis are freshwater amphibious rodents native to Australia. Hippo was rescued after being spotted clinging to a bed of weeds floating down the Murray River after floods in South Australia. At the time she weighed just 63 grams (two ounces). With her umbilical cord still attached and her eyes closed, she was probably only a few days old. Though this is maybe not the most flattering angle, what I love about this image is that it shows two very defining features of rakalis—webbed hind feet and a long tail with a light-colored tip that will become white in adulthood. Taken under the supervision of a wildlife expert. #YourShotPhotographer #rakali #portrait #mammal
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on March 10, 2023.

ph_descripcion:
Photos and video by @GretchenKayStuart | The endangered Old Irish goat arrived in Ireland during the Neolithic Age approximately 5,000 years ago. Over the years the goats were replaced by modern breeds, and only a small number of escaped individuals, who formed wild herds, remained. Due to their impressive horns (Photo 1), the wild goats became a target for trophy hunters, further dwindling the population. Ireland was on track to lose this important part of its heritage to extinction.

In 2021, wildfires fueled by gorse—a flammable, invasive, yellow-flowering shrub—burned for a month and a half in the Dublin suburb of Howth, coming dangerously close to residential neighborhoods (Photo 2). Gorse's dense, prickly nature makes it difficult to manage, but it’s a favorite food of the Old Irish goat, so a brilliant plan took shape …

The Old Irish Goat Society hired herder Melissa Jeuken (Photo 3) and established a conservation grazing program, offering the goats protection while allowing them to roam freely and eat their preferred food in locations at high risk for wildfire.

The goats have made fast work of stripping gorse down to its branches, leaving behind only what is out of reach (Photo 4).

With the success of the conservation grazing program and a new purpose for the goats, the government Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine authorized the Old Irish Goat Society to establish a breeding program and ease the threat of extinction. The goats are DNA tested for genetic integrity before becoming part of the breeding herds.

The work of Jeuken and the Old Irish Goat Society will serve as an example for future conservation grazing programs to be established nationwide.

Swipe to see the video where Jueken calls to a grazing herd, and they emerge from the gorse. “I think this project is neither led by human nor goat but is a joint effort to understand and work together," she says. #OldIrishGoatSociety #OldIrishGoat #yourshotphotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on March 08, 2023. May be an image of nature.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @karimiliya | A young polar bear cub takes a moment to look up. It was amazing to watch this little bear play in the snow, stop to look at birds, and drag her feet while her mother patiently waited. Polar bear mothers have an incredibly difficult job raising their young and hunting on the sea ice, which is only made more complicated by our warming climate. #YourShotPhotographer

ph_descripcion: Photos by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | I believe that fog is a canvas gifted by nature. What we paint on it depends on us. Foggy weather offers a unique opportunity to master the art of seeing in the gray scale of a natural palette. In such situations, I love to create small stories from mundane moments of human activity. I shot these images in the countryside outside my hometown of Muzaffarpur, Bihar, during winter. The restricted palette of black and white allowed me to look at my subjects more deeply, with all the focus on my main story. Sometimes it makes ordinary-looking situations extraordinary. It was really soulful to watch the communication between this unique old banyan tree and the various human activities surrounding it. #YourShotPhotographer

ph_descripcion:
Photos by Michael Seeley @mseeley20 | Liftoff! At 12:34 a.m. ET on March 2, the Crew-6 mission took flight as the Crew Dragon Endeavour spacecraft, carrying four astronauts, was sent to space atop a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket. Launched from historic Launch Complex 39A at NASA's Kennedy Space Center, it’s the sixth commercial crew rotation mission with SpaceX.

Endeavour's international crew consists of NASA astronauts Stephen Bowen and Warren Hoburg, along with astronaut Sultan Al Neyadi of the United Arab Emirates and Roscosmos cosmonaut Andrey Fedyaev. The Dragon capsule will dock with the International Space Station around 1:17 a.m. on Friday, March 3.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on March 02, 2023. May be an image of outdoors.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Laura Gregory @LauraLynPhotography | This brown bear family waits along a salmon-rich stream for an opportunity to catch their next meal. When a sow might be heading to a more dangerous area or when there is a threat, she will sometimes "tree" her cubs. Treeing cubs is when a sow will exert behaviors, such as leaning up against a desired tree, huffing, jaw-popping, and/or looking up the tree, to indicate the cubs should climb it. Cubs can stay up there for a few moments or hours, until the sow returns or the threat is gone. #YourShotPhotographer #KatmaiNationalPark #BrownBear

ph_descripcion: Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | Floating Taj | Reading the fog and its formation during winters near the river belt is quite interesting. The Taj Mahal is one of my favorite monuments in India. I love to shoot it as many times as I can. After a long gap of more than two years due to COVID-19, I visited Agra for a day in December 2022. By reading the formation of the layers of fog behind the Taj, I spotted the right place, then waited in order to get more depth in my composition. At sunrise, I finally captured some moments with golden light on the Taj. #YourShotPhotographer #TajMahal #India

ph_descripcion: Photo by Andrei Stoica @ArizonaPhotoAdventures | Scorpion Arch is an outstanding natural arch located in Arizona’s Arrastra Mountain Wilderness. This is one of a handful of freestanding arches located in Arizona and looks very similar to Delicate Arch in Utah, although at a smaller scale. After a lot of scouting, I was able to locate this arch and, along with a photographer friend, put together a trip last weekend. Getting to the arch and back to the main road required some bushwhacking and route finding, scrapes and all, but all that trouble paid off with some great sunset images and wonderful night shots like this star trails composite taken over half an hour and combining more than 30 images. #YourShotPhotographer

ph_descripcion: Photos by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | The night-blooming cereus, or flowering cactus, is part of a unique species that blooms at night (some plants bloom only one night a year). These magnificent flowers live for only a short time, so it is truly a sight to see when the blooms occur here in Southern California in the summertime. I chose to photograph the flowers from several different angles to capture their beautiful curves, textures and colors. #YourShotPhotographer

ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These photos were taken as part of a project documenting dress fashion in The Gambia. The models were contestants on a reality TV show called “Face Africa Runway Project,” and the dresses came from their wardrobes. Anna Sambou (first photo) educated me about the dresses after a shoot. She explained that the formal dresses are used for events like weddings (a bride can have as many as five dresses), naming ceremonies (babies are named seven days after they are born), and Muslim holidays such as Eid. She also told me that each dress is unique, as they are custom-made by local tailors with fabrics handpicked by the dress recipient. Models in order of appearance: Yasmin Jobe, Binta Bah, Majobe Badjie, Safiatou Willan, Abulai Cisse, Nancy Fatima Riley, Isatou Suso, Veralyn Cecelia George, Adama Faye, Amie Kinteh, Kolawole Dorcas, Mariama Singhateh, Binta Camara, Fatou Keita, Adama Barrow, and Elizabeth Ajang. #yourshotphotographer #africandress #africanfashion #gambia
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on February 01, 2023. May be an image of 1 person.

Photo by @irina_sigl_photography | Near my hometown in Upper Bavaria is an almost 1,000-meter-high (3,280-foot-high) hill that’s home to what is said to be the oldest mountain weather station in the world. When there is high fog in the valley, the view is often clear, and there’s a fantastic view of the clouds from above, all the way to the Alps. On this cold winter evening, the light of the setting sun transformed the landscape into a magical fairyland.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | A thick, foggy marine layer rolls in off the coast of Encinitas, California. The humidity from the fog plays an important role in preventing wildfires, as the moist air coats chaparral and other regional flora. This is particularly vital during the summer months, when the weather in Southern California is hot and dry. I was awestruck while shooting the massive barrel of fog as it rolled in toward the shore. Soon, I was enveloped by the misty air and could barely see anything around me. Nature is truly spectacular! #YourShotPhotographer #marinelayer #wildfireprevention
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on January 17, 2023.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @sarmistha_bera | Jodhpur, the second largest city in Rajasthan, is also called the Blue City. A large portion of Jodhpur has been painted blue, and the Old City has wonderful examples of this vivid color. Some locals we spoke to believe that the blue color keeps the interiors of houses cool during hot summer days. Others said that in the past, several historic buildings were damaged by termites, and it’s believed that the blue hue keeps termites at bay, as the pigment is a mixture of copper sulphate and limestone, which acts as an effective fungicide and bactericide. Still others say the color is associated closely with the Brahmins, India's priestly caste, and the blue houses of the Old City belonged to families of that caste. #YourShotPhotographer #color #travel #India
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on January 02, 2023. May be an image of text that says '野 प्राचीन जेता जेताबेरा बेरा वार्डसं. सं. 20 जाद निगम च्र TU r 0AVO'.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @ketankhambhatta | When it comes to food, a male lion gets the right to eat first. Lionesses and cubs normally wait for the male to give access to a carcass. ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These are portraits of Ebrima "Eazi" Jallow, a fitness model and workout instructor in The Gambia, and his baby Musa, named after his late father. I asked him about fatherhood and he said, “I always dreamed of being a father … Many things changed in my life when I became a dad because I became responsible and worked harder to see my son get the best life. My father was my hero and best friend and gave me the best life, treating me like a prince. I never lacked anything … That is why I named my son after him. I wish my son could meet him. My dad would be very happy and be a good grandfather to my son. I learned a lot from my dad. He was so caring and understanding and gave me advice on how to be a better man in [our] society. I am going to raise my son the same way my dad raised me. I want to give my son a better life and everything in the world because he is the best thing to ever happen to me.” #yourshotphotographer #fatherhood #gambia #baby #fatherson

ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These are portraits of Ebrima "Eazi" Jallow, a fitness model and workout instructor in The Gambia, and his baby Musa, named after his late father. I asked him about fatherhood and he said, “I always dreamed of being a father … Many things changed in my life when I became a dad because I became responsible and worked harder to see my son get the best life. My father was my hero and best friend and gave me the best life, treating me like a prince. I never lacked anything … That is why I named my son after him. I wish my son could meet him. My dad would be very happy and be a good grandfather to my son. I learned a lot from my dad. He was so caring and understanding and gave me advice on how to be a better man in [our] society. I am going to raise my son the same way my dad raised me. I want to give my son a better life and everything in the world because he is the best thing to ever happen to me.” #yourshotphotographer #fatherhood #gambia #baby #fatherson
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on December 22, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Jenny Wong @jdubcaptures | A calm mind and still heart is needed as you anticipate a long exposure of the untamable ocean. My tip for shooting seascapes is to take the time to understand the rhythm and power that shapes the water against the stubborn shoreline, see its many iterations, and become fluent enough to anticipate the shape you desire. The ocean is as dynamic as any living subject, and capturing its mood and personality requires some acquaintance. Quirpon Island, Newfoundland.

Nikon Z7 with Nikkor 16-35mm f4.0. ND64/PL filter. #YourShotPhotographer #Newfoundland #seascape #LongExposure
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on December 21, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Jassen Todorov @jassensf | The Maracanã, a football (soccer) stadium in Rio de Janeiro, is especially impressive when viewed from above. The stadium was built in 1950 to host the FIFA World Cup. In the final game, Uruguay defeated Brazil 2-1 in front of almost 200,000 spectators. Renovated in 2013, the rebuilt stadium hosted several matches in the 2014 FIFA World Cup, including the final game in which Germany defeated Argentina 1-0. With almost 80,000 seats, Maracanã is currently the largest stadium in Brazil. This image was taken from a doors-off helicopter at sunrise.

Nikon D810, 70-200 mm. #YourShotPhotographer #Maracanã #stadium #aerial #photography
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on December 17, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | Sea lions laze on a buoy, with the Santa Margarita Mountains in the distance. Thanks to the Marine Mammal Protection Act, there has been an increase in the sea lion population since 1975, so it’s common to spot these eared seals relaxing along the California coast. ph_descripcion: Photo by Haitham AL Farsi @farsihaitham | The waterfall at Wadi Darbat is a seasonal waterfall that descends only after heavy rain. The monsoon winds (known locally as Khareef) affect the southeastern part of the Arabian Peninsula. In Oman, particularly Dhofar, it is considered a season of life, when mist and fogs cover the mountains, resulting in thriving plants and animals. The season starts in June, and by mid-September, another story begins. This image was created during a licensed drone flight and was taken in accordance with local regulations. #YourShotPhotographer #Oman

Photos by Jassen Todorov @jassensf | With a capacity of almost 95,000, the FNB Stadium, also known as the Calabash or Soccer City, is Africa's largest stadium. Located in Johannesburg, the stadium hosted the 2010 FIFA World Cup, including the opening and final games. The stadium was also the site of a speech by Nelson Mandela following his release from prison in 1990, as well as the memorial service for him in 2013. These three images were taken while I was flying a single-engine Cessna 177 plane.

Nikon D810, 70-200 mm. #YourShotPhotographer #SouthAfrica #stadium #aerial #photography

ph_descripcion: Photo by @victorlimaphoto | The Monjes de La Pacana are huge monoliths found in the Salar de Tara region of the Atacama Desert in Chile. With varied formats, and appearing completely out of nowhere in the middle of the desert, these monoliths stand out in the landscape and give an extraterrestrial air to the region's scenery. Shooting at night at the Monjes de La Pacana is a challenging and very fun task. It’s especially challenging because of the altitude—above 4,000 meters (13,000 feet)—and the intense cold, which can easily reach -10ºC (14ºF) even outside winter. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on December 04, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These are portraits of Naila, a gay makeup artist of South Asian descent who works in the LGBTQIA2S+ community, and model Romone Lenworth Thomas, who also identifies as gay. Makeup has been integral to our community, giving us a means for self-expression, showing the beauty of our diverse identities, and challenging gender norms. We did this shoot in honor of Pride Month in Toronto. Naila writes: “I honor each individual’s unique aesthetic, beauty, and spirit in my work. My creativity and connection to my community give me joy and strength!” Romone writes: “Sometimes, you have to come to terms with loving yourself in spite of what other people may say about you or how they judge you based on your ethnicity, gender, and sexual orientation. Life for me was been hard as a gay Black man. However, through all the twists and turns in life, what really counts is how you rise to keep going to accomplish your goals.” #yourshotphotographer #makeup #pride #lgbtq
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on November 28, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @doug_gimesy | Fighting the Heat | Australia’s gray-headed flying foxes (Pteropus poliocephalus) are a keystone species. They are vital long-distance pollinators and seed disbursers, contributing to the reproductive, evolutionary, and regenerative processes of forest communities along much of Australia’s east coast. Sustained habitat destruction and camp disturbance, however, have decimated the population; it’s about 10 percent of what it was pre- European settlement.

In 2019 and 2020, drought and bush fire food shortages, followed by multiple extreme-heat stress events, took a further toll, killing thousands.

At one of Victoria’s most significant colonies (Yarra Bend Park, Melbourne, in Wurundjeri Country), as temperatures in the shade exceeded 40°C (104ºF) over several days, it is estimated that at least 5,000 perished, or about 10 percent of the colony’s peak summer size. Of these fatalities, about half were less than a year old.

To help during this awful time, and in extreme conditions, dedicated professionals and volunteers worked to save those they could help—and to collect those they couldn’t.

This series captures some of the events during and after those awful days, in order.

(1) The silhouette of a flying fox with wings out, trying to cool down

(2) Firefighters trying to cool the flying foxes by hosing some down

(3) Hundreds clumping and panting, a sign of significant heat stress

(4) A veterinarian giving fluids to a rescued pup

(5) A park ranger passing just a few hundred of the many flying foxes that died

(6) A recent image of a mother flying fox in flight, carrying the next generation

Sadly, with increasing climate change impacts, it is expected that these types of catastrophic events will increase in frequency and severity, putting this already threatened species under greater risk. #flyingfox #fruitbat #climatechange #heatstress #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on November 22, 2022.

Sustained habitat destruction and camp disturbance, however, have decimated the population; it’s about 10 percent of what it was pre- European settlement.

In 2019 and 2020, drought and bush fire food shortages, followed by multiple extreme-heat stress events, took a further toll, killing thousands.

At one of Victoria’s most significant colonies (Yarra Bend Park, Melbourne, in Wurundjeri Country), as temperatures in the shade exceeded 40°C (104ºF) over several days, it is estimated that at least 5,000 perished, or about 10 percent of the colony’s peak summer size. Of these fatalities, about half were less than a year old.

To help during this awful time, and in extreme conditions, dedicated professionals and volunteers worked to save those they could help—and to collect those they couldn’t.

This series captures some of the events during and after those awful days, in order.

(1) The silhouette of a flying fox with wings out, trying to cool down

(2) Firefighters trying to cool the flying foxes by hosing some down

(3) Hundreds clumping and panting, a sign of significant heat stress

(4) A veterinarian giving fluids to a rescued pup

(5) A park ranger passing just a few hundred of the many flying foxes that died

(6) A recent image of a mother flying fox in flight, carrying the next generation

Sadly, with increasing climate change impacts, it is expected that these types of catastrophic events will increase in frequency and severity, putting this already threatened species under greater risk. #flyingfox #fruitbat #climatechange #heatstress #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on November 22, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @victorlimaphoto | The Milky Way's core hovers over Piedras Rojas in the Atacama Desert, Chile. Piedras Rojas is located about 150 kilometers (93 miles) from San Pedro de Atacama and at an altitude above 4,300 meters (14,000 feet). Far from any source of light pollution and accessible by the main road that crosses the Atacama, the sky in this place is certainly one of the most incredible on the planet.

In this image, with only 25 seconds of exposure, I was able to capture, with a good level of detail, the nucleus of the Milky Way and also the nebulae present in this portion of the sky, in addition to the beautiful airglow that gives color and brightness to the horizon. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on November 16, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Michael Seeley @mseeley20 | Launched at 7:05 p.m. ET on Saturday, October 8, 2022, the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket carried the Intelsat Galaxy 33 and Galaxy 34 communications satellites into orbit. As the rocket climbed, it passed in front of the nearly full hunter's moon, seen here from Titusville, Florida.

The launch took place five minutes after sunset, so there was still quite a bit of light in the sky, and the moonrise was at 6:37 p.m., so the moon, 99 percent illuminated, was only 5.65 degrees high. Because the moon was so low and the rocket's trajectory was east, it was reasonably easy to use a tool like the Photographer's Ephemeris to determine where to stand to position the moon above the pad at ignition time.

The rocket causes an interesting effect as it passes in front of the moon. Kent Gee, chair of the physics and astronomy department at Brigham Young University, explained on Twitter that "[t]he ripples you see across the moon's face are caused by high-intensity acoustic waves. The steep pressure gradient changes the light's index of refraction. These Mach waves are present in supersonic jet flows."
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on November 04, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | In Rwanda there is no food service at hospitals. If a hospitalized individual does not have a caregiver to bring food and assist with feeding (if needed) the patient can suffer from malnutrition during recovery. At a hospital in the district of Butare, local nonprofit Growing Health Rwanda has planted a 13-acre (5-hectare) organic farm and food forest on-site to feed new mothers in recovery. The food forest also acts as a demonstration garden for local farmers, who learn agro-based tree planting to help prevent erosion, replenish nutrients in the soil, and provide food and income for their families. I used a 135mm lens to photograph people in the community, including farmers, who participate in this effort. #YourShotPhotographer #rwanda #foodforest
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on October 27, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | Pencil Art | The minimalistic approach in photography is one of the most difficult to execute, as we have to tell stories silently that may have various interpretations. It’s a kind of visual art, with minimum elements in the frame and greater breathing space. This breathing space creates a meditative, musical feel to me. During my childhood, I loved to draw minimalistic art pieces with pencil on paper. Now with my camera, I still love to create similar visual stories whenever I am able to find a situation like this. I composed this moment from a bridge in my hometown of Muzaffarpur, Bihar, in October 2020, during the first wave of the COVID-19 pandemic. #YourShotPhotographer

#India

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Michael Seeley @mseeley20 | Welcome to the Sunshine State. That’s American Airlines flight AA1837—traveling from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, to West Palm Beach, Florida—passing in front of the sun, photographed from the Space Coast of Florida (Melbourne). The Airbus A321 was flying at 26,000 feet (7,925 meters) and 426 knots.

This image was captured using a Canon R5 + RF100-500mm lens with a 1.4x teleconverter with a proper solar filter, which is why the sky around the sun is black. Also needed was a lot of patience and luck. I've become accustomed to knowing roughly when the sun and moon are near the flight corridors near my house, but a transit like this is lucky, and before getting this one, I'd had 50 or more near (or total) misses. This one worked surprisingly (and satisfyingly) well. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on October 02, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @victorlimaphoto | The Milky Way's core hovers over Piedras Rojas in the Atacama Desert, Chile. Piedras Rojas is located about 150 kilometers (93 miles) from San Pedro de Atacama and at an altitude above 4,300 meters (14,000 feet). Far from any source of light pollution and accessible by the main road that crosses the Atacama, the sky in this place is certainly one of the most incredible on the planet.

In this image, with only 25 seconds of exposure, I was able to capture, with a good level of detail, the nucleus of the Milky Way and also the nebulae present in this portion of the sky, in addition to the beautiful airglow that gives color and brightness to the horizon. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 29, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Jenny Wong @jdubcaptures | As we crossed Admiralty Inlet from Brodeur Peninsula to Borden Peninsula on Baffin Island, we hit rough ice that was decorated with evidence of life. There were prints in every direction, some fresh, some windblown-old. With some prints you can determine freshness just by looking at them; with others our guides would feel the texture of the snow. The polar bears were clearly here for a good reason—rough ice provided great cover as they sniffed out seals. And boy, was there seal activity here. The prints in this image led to a seal breathing hole, the abrupt lump in the ice, top middle of frame. The bear doubled back to the den that was clearly smashed in, and just a few feet away on the pristine snow were the frozen splatters of a successful kill. The missing carcass was likely scavenged and cached by the fox whose prints circled the splatter. We don’t always see the wildlife we hope to see when we’re in the field, but sights like this one are sometimes just as fun and interesting. Being out and getting to share the ice with these creatures and having Inuit guides to teach and help interpret with us is a blessing in itself. After all, for wildlife photographers it is these teaching moments that make us better.

Nikon Z7 with adapted NIKKOR 16-35mm f/4.0 G ED VR. #YourShotPhotographer #Nunavut #polarbears #seaice
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 25, 2022.

Photo by @hamishfrost | A team bivvying on the Cuillin Ridge on the Isle of Skye in Scotland. The 12-kilometer-long (7-mile-long) ridge takes in some of the finest scrambling and mountaineering terrain in the U.K., with many teams opting to split a full traverse over two days and spend a night sleeping up high on the ridge.

iPhone 13 Pro, 13mm, 1/160s, f/1.8, ISO 32. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 24, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @trikansh_sharma | Baya weavers are nature's best engineers, building some incredible nests. Every year during the monsoons, they make nests around my city, Rishikesh, India, and I keep looking for them in different places in an effort to compose something unique rather than just click portraits of these birds. When I fixed my frame, the game of waiting began, as the male baya weaver was busy making his house perfect so that a female would be impressed and he could mate with her. The moment the male came into my frame, I made these images. #YourShotPhotographer #bayaweaver #art #silhouettes #composition
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 19, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | A monarch butterfly rests on the leaves of a strawberry tree in Leucadia, California. The pink flowers of the strawberry tree are a great source of nectar for monarchs, making this evergreen shrub a wonderful addition to any garden. The more pesticide-free habitats we can provide for these amazing creatures, the better chance they will have at surviving climate change. To achieve the beautiful blue background in this photo, I waited patiently until the monarch flew to a part of the tree where the sky was positioned behind it. #YourShotPhotographer #monarchbutterfly

ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These are portraits of Rajiyah Rizwan, a 17-year-old self-taught henna/mehndi artist and owner of Henna Boutique, and model Kirti Saxena. Rajiyah started applying henna 10 years ago for Eid celebrations. Rajiyah writes, “Henna, or mehndi, is a powder made from henna plants. It dates back to 9,000 years ago in Egypt. Henna is mainly practiced by Pakistani, Indian, African, and Middle Eastern cultures. There are many techniques used in henna art. I use draping—squeezing henna out of a cone in fine, silky lines. I use lotuses in my art, as flowers symbolize purity and new beginnings.” Kirti associates henna with Indian traditions such as weddings and believes that it brings women together. Kirti was mesmerized as Rajiyah created the henna design freestyle for this shoot. She says, “The process makes you feel beautiful and empowered. As a woman of color, mehndi highlights my culture and symbols that mean a lot to me.” #yourshotphotographer #henna
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 13, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @GretchenKayStuart | The adorable feral bunnies of Cannon Beach, Oregon, originated with a local family that released pet rabbits in 1982. The bunnies adapted to their environment and multiplied. Today they are abundant and surviving as if wild—but, of course, they’re not native. Their presence is loved by tourists but less loved by locals, who have witnessed them being killed by birds of prey or suffering due to overgrown molars and inclement weather. Most of the bunnies are small and young. This is because their lifespans are significantly shortened by car strikes, poisoning, and lack of proper nutrients in their diets. Moral of the story: Don’t abandon your bunnies! #CannonBeach #FeralBunny #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 10, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | I shot these moments in a lychee orchard in my hometown of Muzaffarpur—famous for high-quality lychee production—in the state of Bihar, India. It’s an important subtropical evergreen crop that is transported to the rest of India. The high-quality lychee, known as shahi lychee, is also exported to other countries. Lychee being exacting in its climatic requirements, it is confined to a few states, with almost 75 percent of production recorded in Bihar. Here, lychee is the livelihood for millions of people, as it provides both on-farm and off-farm employment. The domestic market generally receives lychee in 10- to 12-kilogram (22- to 26-pound) wooden cages or baskets. With a narrow genetic base, under given climatic conditions this fruit is available for only three to four weeks, from the second week of May to the third week of June. #YourShotPhotographer #India
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 09, 2022.

Lychee being exacting in its climatic requirements, it is confined to a few states, with almost 75 percent of production recorded in Bihar. Here, lychee is the livelihood for millions of people, as it provides both on-farm and off-farm employment. The domestic market generally receives lychee in 10- to 12-kilogram (22- to 26-pound) wooden cages or baskets. With a narrow genetic base, under given climatic conditions this fruit is available for only three to four weeks, from the second week of May to the third week of June. #YourShotPhotographer #India
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 09, 2022.

Photo by @irina_sigl_photography | The beech forests of Jasmund National Park on the island of Rügen in northern Germany are a UNESCO World Heritage site and incredibly impressive.

Looking from the ground into the crowns of the mighty trees, it feels as if the giant trees have gathered to communicate with each other. It is fascinating to observe that their crowns do not touch and respectfully keep their distance from each other, a phenomenon known as crown shyness.

Nikon Z7, 14mm, f4, 1/500s, ISO200. #YourShotPhotographer #Trees #Germany #Rügen
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 08, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | The colors and textures of the Batiquitos Lagoon are illuminated at sunset. Located in Carlsbad, California, the 610-acre (247 hectare) lagoon underwent a large restoration project in the mid-1990s to open a tidal inlet to the ocean and create greater habitat value. (The lagoon was previously a confined nontidal system.) Nearly 200 prehistoric sites have been found in the area, some dating back 8,000 years. Wildlife populations—particularly those of birds and fish—have increased in number and diversity since the restoration. Tarps draped over the surrounding bluffs serve as a reminder of the fragility of this ever changing landscape. #YourShotPhotographer #lagoons
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on September 02, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @GretchenKayStuart | In order to protect the kittens, I’ve waited over six months to share this encounter. Here’s the story behind the shot!

I had been exploring the Northern California trails for a couple of weeks when I came upon this family of three. Mom was teaching her kittens to hunt from the beams of an old fence at an abandoned barn. As I observed from a distance, a family of four deer ran through, startling the kittens. One kitten ran up a eucalyptus tree, and the other hid in some tall grass. Mom, who is pretty fierce judging by the scars on her nose and ears, stayed on the fence giving the deer a squinting glare of annoyance. After the deer passed, Mom gave one call, and the smaller kitten came down from the tree and started making very subtle calls to its sibling. The calls were so quiet that I couldn’t hear them but could only observe the kitten’s mouth moving through my lens. Once the larger kitten joined, the mother led them in my direction. It was an absolutely surreal experience as all three posed on the log in front of me and made eye contact, allowing me to make a perfect family portrait.

As with all of my photography, these bobcats are wild, not baited, and shot at an ethical distance with a long lens. When photographing wildlife, the well-being of the animals should always be the top priority. #BobcatKittens #CaliforniaWildlife #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on August 24, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Maria Russo @mariaaaugust | This alien-like marine animal is a sea anemone, a close relative of coral and jellyfish that lives in the intertidal zone of all oceans. Named after a terrestrial flowering plant, sea anemones use nematocysts—microscopic stinging structures in the tentacles—to capture prey and to protect themselves against predators. The sea anemone featured in this photo is known as a starburst anemone because of its colors, which vary from green to white with lavender-, pink-, and blue-tipped tentacles. I took this image while admiring a tide pool along the coast of Encinitas, California. #YourShotPhotographer #seaanemone
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on August 17, 2022.

Photo by Jassen Todorov @jassensf | Trees are glorious. Countless beautiful creatures, small and large, reside in forests. Sadly, dozens of destructive wildfires have recently obliterated numerous forests in the western United States. This image portrays the devastation caused by the Dixie fire, California's largest single wildfire. This aerial was taken while I was flying my Piper Warrior single-engine plane. Please note this is not a black-and-white photo.

Nikon D810, 70-200mm. #YourShotPhotographer #DixieFire #California #Aerial #Photography
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on August 17, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by @sarmistha_bera | Gajoldoba in North Bengal, India, is a vast, beautiful wetland full of birds. In the past few years, I’ve come to learn how much photography can teach us about life. And how much we are learning about photography every day. As with street photographers, I admire nature and wildlife photographers, realizing how long they need to wait for the right moment to frame a perfect shot. I respect their dedication and patience. Here are a few of the bird photographs that I took on my last trip in December 2022, after pandemic restrictions were relaxed. Pictured: ruddy shelduck, common redshank, river lapwing, common teal, red-crested pochard. #YourShotPhotographer #nature #india #birds
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on August 15, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
Photo by Jenny Wong @jdubcaptures | One of the three to four hundred wild plains bison that roam the enclosed Elk Island National Park. This herd has played an integral role in bison conservation. At one point in the early 1900s it was one of the last remaining purebred and disease-free herds. Since then members of this herd has been relocated around the world to repopulate the grasslands where they once roamed. The survival of bison locally and rescue from near extinction globally is one of the greatest conservation stories in Canada.

Nikon Z 7, 200-500mm. #YourShotPhotographer #Bison #Conservation
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on August 09, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | Smelling the Bricks | An early morning moment at the brickmaking factory. In photography our role is to observe the scene, observe the mood, observe the moment, and finally give them our own voices so that we can communicate the right story. ph_descripcion: Photo by Takashi Nakazawa @takashi_photography | At Lake Tanuki, just west of Mount Fuji, there are days, only twice a year, when the morning sun rises from the summit of Mount Fuji. ph_descripcion: Photo by @GretchenKayStuart | Fellow wildlife photographers know the feeling that accompanies a rare sighting of an elusive species, and this encounter with a baby Pacific marten fully delivered that rush of joy we live for! I was hiking on a remote trail on Mount Rainier when there was a bustle in the trees ahead. I sat down and watched as two baby martens chased each other up and down the conifers. Soon, the brave one noticed me and came down for a closer look. I was likely the first human this tiny being had ever laid eyes on, and the curiosity level was high. This unexpected encounter is a memory that will forever make me smile! #PacificMarten #MountRainier #YourShotPhotographer

ph_descripcion:
Photo by @irina_sigl_photography | I love trees! Especially huge and venerable ones. Looking at them from below and seeing their mighty treetops reaching for the sky is fascinating and interesting. If you look closely you can see that their tops never touch, as if they had agreed with each other to keep a respectful distance and still be close. I captured these beautiful beech trees in Jasmund National Park on the island of Rügen, Germany. The beech forest is recognized on UNESCO’s World Heritage List.

Nikon Z7, 14mm, f11, 1/250s, ISO200.

#YourShotPhotographer #Tree #Rügen #Germany

ph_descripcion: Photo by @karimiliya | Over the years, foxes have gotten a bad reputation. Traditionally we have hunted them for their fur or because they get into chicken coops. However, they are incredibly curious and very intelligent animals. I was incredibly lucky to spend more than four hours watching and photographing this little arctic fox as it ate the carcass of a reindeer on the side of a mountain at sunset in Svalbard. For a moment, it stopped eating and came so close that my camera could not even focus. In summer it will wear a darker coat so that it can blend into the landscape better. #YourShotPhotographer

Photo by Haitham AL Farsi @farsihaitham | Congratulations to Haitham AL Farsi on becoming the May 2022 Your Shot Photographer of the Month! Each month, we select a Your Shot Photographer who produced stunning work and fostered a sense of community.

The sardine season in Oman’s Dhofar Governorate is one of the most important annual seasons, as local fishers use traditional fishing methods. The season starts at the beginning of October, after the end of the monsoon season, which is accompanied by strong waves that make fishing difficult. In the picture, a fisher is shown carrying nets filled with sardines, and around him are hundreds of seagulls, which are also waiting for their share of fish. #YourShotPhotographer #oman #Dhofar #Salalah

ph_descripcion: Photos by @justin_anantawan | These are photos of Vaughan Murrae, a nonbinary teen actor/model, and their mom, Annastacia. Vaughan first came out as transmasculine to their parents, who were supportive. In grade four, when they cut their hair short, they were mocked by classmates and called a boy. Constant bullying led to anxiety and panic attacks. They also felt gender dysphoria, as a trans identity did not fit them. In grade six, they saw an Instagram post about they/them pronouns and realized they were nonbinary. When they texted their mom, she responded, “I’m already practicing [your new pronouns].” Annastacia says that she struggled with biases about gender discovery and felt pressure as a mom to make them more decisive. ph_descripcion: Photo by @karimiliya | The mighty sperm whale, the largest toothed predator on the planet, with the biggest brain. These are highly intelligent, skilled hunters that dive down into the depths of the ocean and use sonar to battle giant squid. There is so much lore surrounding these animals, often depicted as violent beasts that would sink whaling ships and kill the sailors. The reality is that they are gentle, sentient beings with complex communication and strong social bonds. They live in pods and care for their young. If you treat them with respect, they are very gentle and often curious. I’ve been photographing different whale species for years, but it’s hard to put into words what it’s like to swim with a sperm whale and feel the clicks of their echolocation scanning your body. It can make you feel very vulnerable but also humble. While the adults were hunting in the deep, I swam alongside this little calf, looking into her eye and wondering what was going on in her giant brain. Watching the tiny little fish around her gave me a sense of scale and an appreciation for how big and small life can be, with each being playing a vital role in life on this planet. Taken under permit. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on June 13, 2022.

ph_descripcion:
This is eight-year-old Oban Birmingham. He has always been passionate about nature and curious about how animals are photographed. In October 2020, Oban was diagnosed with Burkitt leukemia, a rare form of cancer. Throughout his treatment Oban remained resilient, and his passion for wildlife grew while watching countless nature documentaries in the hospital and visiting the local nature preserve when home.

After bravely finishing chemotherapy in April 2021, Oban was contacted by the Make-A-Wish Foundation. His wish was to join a National Geographic Explorer in the field. He was told it would take some time to coordinate, but Oban was happy to wait for his wish.

In February 2022, Oban's wish came true. He spent the day photographing local wildlife with National Geographic Explorer and photographer Carlton Ward Jr. (@carltonward) at the Corkscrew Swamp Sanctuary in Naples, Florida.

This is where Oban captured the photo of the American white ibis. Carlton taught Oban about his camera equipment, the Florida Wildlife Corridor, and the specific techniques he uses, such as camera trapping, to capture wildlife on location.

Looking toward the future, Oban aspires to be a naturalist for National Geographic when he grows up.

Your Shot Editor Select of the American white ibis by Oban Birmingham

Make-A-Wish photos by Zee Anna Photography
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on June 02, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @justin_anantawan | This is a self-portrait that I am dedicating to all people living with HIV (PHAs), as I am HIV-positive. I have had low self-esteem due to the stigma of HIV. For example, I have felt dirty when potential partners have asked me if I am "clean" when asking about my HIV status. I have heard people at work make jokes about HIV, saying it can be spread by sharing drinks. A doctor shamed me after my diagnosis with the word "sloppy." The HIV stigma negatively affects the mental health of PHAs and can lead to issues like nonadherence to medication and suicide. The HIV stigma prevents people from getting tested. Society needs to know that with proper medication folks living with HIV can lead healthy, normal lives and not transmit HIV to other people (when a PHA takes their HIV medication regularly, their viral load is undetectable, making HIV intransmissible). People living with HIV deserve to feel loved, included, worthy, and beautiful. #yourshotphotographer #hiv #uequalsu
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on June 01, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photos by Michael Seeley @mseeley20 | Viewed from the Rocket Garden at Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex is the super flower blood moon, captured during the total eclipse period between 11:29 p.m. on May 15 and 12:53 a.m. on May 16. The first photo shows the Juno II rocket, active between 1958 and 1961. The second photo shows the moon next to the Atlas-Agena rocket. This rocket had 93 successful launches from 1960 to 1978, including the Ranger and Lunar Orbiter missions to the moon. The third photo is a wide view of the moon over the Delta II rocket (vertical) and the Saturn 1B rocket (horizontal). The Saturn 1B was integral to the Apollo program’s mission to land astronauts on the moon. The fourth photo shows the moon at maximum eclipse. #YourShotPhotographer
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on May 20, 2022.

Photo by Michel Godimus @yosomono.photography | Congratulations to Michel Godimus on becoming the April 2022 Your Shot Photographer of the Month! Each month, we select a Your Shot Photographer who produced stunning work and fostered a sense of community.

A vixen and her cub are resting and cuddling tenderly. This photo shows the striking difference between the brown eyes of an adult fox and the blue eyes of a newborn fox. The kit was all black a week ago, but it is starting to take on the colors of an adult fox from the head down. As long as it has blue eyes, it has very poor eyesight, but its already well-developed senses of hearing and smell allow it to compensate for its still weak eyesight.
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on May 11, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Navin Kumar @navinvatsa | Some moments we capture can define a journey from the rich past to the current decade we are living in. It’s a kind of visual narration that is sometimes enough to show many things with just a single image. Jami Masjid is at the Feroz Shah Kotla fort in Delhi, India. Once this mosque had a large prayer hall; now only its ruins are visible, like an open terrace, and used to offer prayer. During the month of Ramadan, especially on Eid, it offers a beautiful sense of place and tradition. On normal days, this place is visited by very few people, but on Eid it has a totally different view. Even its surrounding structures are used to offer prayer/namaz. Here, I tried my best to capture this auspicious moment from an angle that included layers from front to back. #yourshotphotographer #eid #festival #India
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on May 03, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @veronika_k_ko | Ghosts Over Canal Grande | "We live looking at shadows that move and believe that this is reality …" A quote by Jose Saramago I chose for my photograph. It is an abstract I achieved with quite a lot of effort. Visiting Venice once again and fascinated by its beauty but also by the mystique and secrets this city hides, a creative idea came into my head: to drop all this on only one photo. I thought for a while and decided to "draw" ghost silhouettes using a long exposure and movement. After a few attempts, I got what I wanted: In my photo painting I managed to capture the beauty of the city, its beautiful buildings, and the colorful reflections of the lights in the Canal Grande but also the mystical element—all these "ghosts" crossing, flying over, or walking on the water. This is a single shot, handheld, no tripod or editing used. #yourshotphotographer #fineartphotographer #creativeart #photopainting
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on May 03, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by @trikansh_sharma | A male Asian elephant takes a mud bath on a hot summer evening at Corbett Tiger Reserve in India. This behavior is commonly seen in elephants because it helps them to maintain their body temperature. This tusker was in the foothills of the Himalaya, and the sunset was on the top of the mountain, giving me the darker background. The moment the elephant started the mud bath, I clicked multiple frames and chose this one as the best out of that scene. #YourShotPhotographer #AsiaticElephant #CorbettTigerReserve #Himalaya
ph_atributos: Photo by National Geographic Your Shot on May 02, 2022.

ph_descripcion: Photo by Michel Godimus @yosomono.photography / A white-tailed eagle lands on a block of ice. The blocks of ice drifting from Siberia to Hokkaido each winter bring with them many marine animals and other sources of nutrients. They are therefore an important element for the ecosystem of Hokkaido. Unfortunately, the more the years pass, the more the period and quantity of drifting ice decreases. #YourShotPhotographer #Hokkaido #whitetailedeagle
